1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:02,575
So now it's time to eat again.

2
00:00:02,634 --> 00:00:09,025
And just to spend a bit more time reflecting on this process.

3
00:00:11,368 --> 00:00:22,885
So remember that we have to find a way of being with pleasure and the joys of life in a way that it doesn't have this aftermath, this comeback.

4
00:00:24,469 --> 00:00:27,253
Frustration when you can't get it, grief when you lose it,

5
00:00:28,263 --> 00:00:30,306
and take out insurance just in case you do.

6
00:00:30,346 --> 00:00:33,329
All that is underneath.

7
00:00:33,530 --> 00:00:35,912
While we're enjoying stuff, it's not a problem.

8
00:00:35,972 --> 00:00:36,554
Nothing like it.

9
00:00:38,176 --> 00:00:53,555
So, food or eating, which we have to do every day, is just the opportunity to remind ourselves about how to be with pleasure in a non-attached, non-indulgent way.

10
00:00:56,820 --> 00:00:57,561
And,

11
00:00:59,076 --> 00:01:01,142
The beginning is to get the right attitude.

12
00:01:01,923 --> 00:01:12,629
So if there's an attitude in the mind which is going to really enjoy this food, then there's going to be a danger that it's sort of indulging it.

13
00:01:12,709 --> 00:01:16,680
And what we mean by that is that we're seeking happiness in food.

14
00:01:17,132 --> 00:01:18,917
real happiness, lasting happiness.

15
00:01:20,519 --> 00:01:25,870
It's momentary, but it doesn't deliver the ultimate that we're looking for.

16
00:01:27,132 --> 00:01:32,763
So, you have to put the right intention into the mind, which is to nourish the body.

17
00:01:33,585 --> 00:01:35,209
Food is just medicine for the body.

18
00:01:36,656 --> 00:02:01,804
And I do a chanting, it's more formal this lunchtime, I receive the food and then I do a chant which basically says that, that I'm not eating food in order to escape my problems or to add to them or to get for the pleasure of it, I'm just eating the food for the purpose of keeping the body healthy so that I can live the spiritual life.

19
00:02:01,784 --> 00:02:25,968
so that's important to actually when you take your food and you sit in front of it you remind yourself so there's your attitude and this leaves you free to investigate the process around the whole action of eating so as you make your intention to eat you see and you pick up your fork or whatever you see

20
00:02:26,437 --> 00:02:30,383
You know, really begin right at the beginning by contacting the body.

21
00:02:30,643 --> 00:02:32,224
So how does the metal feel?

22
00:02:33,287 --> 00:02:35,650
Begin right there at the sense of touch.

23
00:02:36,911 --> 00:02:44,060
And then as you scoop it and put it into your mouth, just that first delightful explosion on the tongue, you see.

24
00:02:44,640 --> 00:02:45,921
Just stay there right with it.

25
00:02:46,082 --> 00:02:49,526
Keep the attention right on the tongue.

26
00:02:49,507 --> 00:03:01,983
And if you use a word like tasting rather than curry or whatever, then it keeps you attentive to the process that's happening.

27
00:03:03,825 --> 00:03:12,257
And we're just trying to find out what taste is before it fits into some sort of conceptual pattern.

28
00:03:13,164 --> 00:03:17,691
That's another problem we have, that we keep looking at things from history.

29
00:03:17,711 --> 00:03:21,776
We keep looking at things from a past experience.

30
00:03:22,776 --> 00:03:28,925
So we need to get back to a very original mind, which is a direct experience of things.

31
00:03:28,944 --> 00:03:31,228
And it's not that difficult to develop.

32
00:03:32,209 --> 00:03:37,215
It's just a case of keeping the attention very close to the sense base.

33
00:03:38,461 --> 00:03:47,129
So while you're tasting, tasting, tasting, you see, your attention is right there on what's happening at the tongue, what it's doing, how you're chewing.

34
00:03:47,270 --> 00:03:48,931
You're just there with the mechanics of it.

35
00:03:50,014 --> 00:03:51,055
And you're aware of the pleasure.

36
00:03:51,375 --> 00:03:51,855
That's the point.

37
00:03:51,876 --> 00:03:52,937
You're aware of the pleasure.

38
00:03:52,977 --> 00:03:56,580
The pleasure is pleasurable, right?

39
00:03:56,600 --> 00:04:00,185
You don't have to say to yourself, this is pleasurable taste, but it's most unpleasurable.

40
00:04:00,865 --> 00:04:01,825
It's pleasurable taste.

41
00:04:01,926 --> 00:04:06,931
It's a total openness to it, a receiving of what that sense base is giving you.

42
00:04:09,663 --> 00:04:22,047
And it may be that after some time, after you've swallowed the first, you can just stop for a moment and just recognize what's happened within the heart, the emotional base.

43
00:04:22,067 --> 00:04:25,072
Hopefully, it is now in a state of delight.

44
00:04:25,507 --> 00:04:36,524
And to feel that, to get into the feel of it so that you know, well, this is also a form of energy, a form of energy, but it's not the same as the gross physical energy.

45
00:04:37,105 --> 00:04:48,461
And it's making that distinction, deconstructing our experience, which begins to undermine this idea of who I am.

46
00:04:48,913 --> 00:05:02,838
So by disconnecting, as it were, the body with its sense space, with its sensations, and the heart with its more subtle emotional feelings, we're beginning to deconstruct the event, you see.

47
00:05:04,675 --> 00:05:17,047
Then as you, before the next bite or sometime, just to hold on for a minute and just to feel that intention to eat.

48
00:05:17,668 --> 00:05:19,713
Make it very obvious to yourself.

49
00:05:20,452 --> 00:05:26,966
So that intention is coming from a natural base, it's just appetite, the body wanting some sort of nourishment.

50
00:05:27,726 --> 00:05:31,574
But there's also, remember, behind it, this seeking for desire, this seeking for happiness.

51
00:05:32,216 --> 00:05:33,497
Just stay with it, feel it.

52
00:05:34,279 --> 00:05:35,180
Is that an emotion?

53
00:05:35,521 --> 00:05:36,002
What is it?

54
00:05:36,644 --> 00:05:41,213
What is that sort of force that sort of drives us to eat?

55
00:05:42,475 --> 00:05:42,956
What is it?

56
00:05:44,699 --> 00:05:47,142
And it's not a case of an intellectual answer.

57
00:05:47,302 --> 00:05:51,471
It's a case of a direct experience of it.

58
00:05:51,951 --> 00:05:54,776
Normally speaking, all this is just one thing, isn't it?

59
00:05:55,437 --> 00:05:57,240
You know, you go into a restaurant and eat a pizza.

60
00:05:57,581 --> 00:05:58,543
That's it.

61
00:05:59,144 --> 00:06:01,327
It's like it's one experience.

62
00:06:01,307 --> 00:06:04,593
But here we're trying to sort of deconstruct the event, you see.

63
00:06:05,254 --> 00:06:06,214
It's the same with the cinema.

64
00:06:06,276 --> 00:06:09,480
You go in the cinema or watching a VD, it's one experience.

65
00:06:09,500 --> 00:06:14,567
You hear and you're seeing and you're empathizing.

66
00:06:15,009 --> 00:06:17,432
You're doing all sorts of things all in that one moment.

67
00:06:17,452 --> 00:06:20,197
But actually there's a whole load of processes going on, you know.

68
00:06:21,278 --> 00:06:24,583
The hearing isn't the seeing and the seeing isn't the empathizing, see.

69
00:06:24,603 --> 00:06:27,567
So it's really just trying to investigate this.

70
00:06:29,100 --> 00:06:35,572
And remember our purpose is to get to the end of suffering, or to put it more positively, is to be happy, right?

71
00:06:35,612 --> 00:06:38,399
We're trying to get to a decent happiness, that's what we're trying to get to.

72
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:45,793
So this process isn't just a nice little exercise we're doing, we're actually trying to get to a point where...

73
00:06:46,144 --> 00:06:48,428
we're happy, heaven's sake.

74
00:06:49,471 --> 00:07:04,476
So, we've made these three distinctions now, there's the body, there's the heart with its, of course we've got the mind, the mind's, you know, we're using the mind to keep the attention steady, so it's down to one word, so it's not thinking about anything.

75
00:07:04,838 --> 00:07:08,524
See, that's our greatest hindrance, to think about something.

76
00:07:09,043 --> 00:07:12,958
And then we've got this process of the will, right?

77
00:07:13,077 --> 00:07:14,423
The will, intention.

78
00:07:16,348 --> 00:07:21,466
And hopefully there'll come a part of the meal where you get this

79
00:07:21,886 --> 00:07:24,389
this feedback from the body saying enough.

80
00:07:25,449 --> 00:07:32,797
And it's sort of hanging on there with that and just feeling the override and just knowing that that's the old greed.

81
00:07:33,898 --> 00:07:39,704
Now, normally speaking what we would do is just keep eating till even the greed was satisfied.

82
00:07:40,204 --> 00:07:42,387
That's when the body signals back that it's getting sick.

83
00:07:44,069 --> 00:07:47,312
And at that point you might say it's a point of gratification.

84
00:07:47,973 --> 00:07:49,935
So we feel gratified.

85
00:07:50,422 --> 00:07:55,589
and we have a little rest period, and then the old desire rises again.

86
00:07:56,610 --> 00:08:17,442
However, if we stay with the desire and not feed it, we put our attention just on the desire, that wanting, wanting, and just wait for that to fade out, we get to something which feels like gratification, but it's better called contentment, because this is the mind without desire.

87
00:08:19,362 --> 00:08:24,733
Now to know the distinction between being gratified and being contented is crucial.

88
00:08:25,954 --> 00:08:30,545
Because one leads you towards liberation and the other one towards hell.

89
00:08:31,125 --> 00:08:35,193
So it's worth making that distinction.

90
00:08:35,748 --> 00:08:43,815
Now it may be that you've taken a little too much food and you've got this food left and your body's telling you actually you've had enough.

91
00:08:43,835 --> 00:08:44,836
So now you've got a choice.

92
00:08:44,976 --> 00:08:50,642
You can either stuff it into your body knowing it's not going to do the body any good or throw it away and feel guilty.

93
00:08:51,802 --> 00:08:56,947
Because all these people, especially these days, are having a shortage of food in some areas.

94
00:08:57,948 --> 00:09:03,813
So now, what I would suggest you do

95
00:09:04,620 --> 00:09:06,904
is that you throw it away and feel guilty.

96
00:09:08,567 --> 00:09:16,600
And the reason for that is that as you contact your guilt and really feel it, you see, that then becomes your guardian.

97
00:09:17,741 --> 00:09:21,568
Because the next time you approach food, you'll say to yourself, now I don't want to feel that guilt again.

98
00:09:22,831 --> 00:09:23,311
That's horrible.

99
00:09:23,932 --> 00:09:30,442
So you take a little less and there's always a chance of getting some more food afterwards.

100
00:09:30,591 --> 00:09:31,332
Yeah?

101
00:09:31,352 --> 00:09:38,102
So, even though that's not PC, that's what I would suggest you do.

102
00:09:38,923 --> 00:09:40,005
And feel the guilt.

103
00:09:43,390 --> 00:09:49,099
Then, when it comes to the end of the meal, you see, just stop for a minute and just recollect.

104
00:09:49,239 --> 00:09:51,261
What was it you've experienced?

105
00:09:51,282 --> 00:09:58,152
This recollection is important because it makes you revisit those places, you see,

106
00:09:59,009 --> 00:10:05,458
And by doing that, it becomes a sort of habit in the mind, a moment of reflection.

107
00:10:08,743 --> 00:10:10,686
It's one of the things the Buddha constantly goes on about.

108
00:10:12,489 --> 00:10:17,996
Yoniso manesikāra, it means right attention, right reflection, to think about things properly.

109
00:10:19,477 --> 00:10:26,566
Now, after the meal, there's a little break there, and what is good to practice there is this quiet abiding.

110
00:10:27,245 --> 00:10:31,390
So there's these three factors that lead to enlightenment.

111
00:10:31,791 --> 00:10:38,538
The calmness, calmness of the body, calmness of the heart.

112
00:10:38,558 --> 00:10:46,486
Even if you feel agitated or the heart's very troubled or whatever, you can still, as it were, take it for a walk.

113
00:10:47,408 --> 00:10:48,809
Just relax around it.

114
00:10:49,802 --> 00:11:09,717
steadiness of attention that's always there so you have to keep the noting going or else the mind will just wander and this attitude of just receiving just receiving not doing anything about anything and just dropping for a while the inquisity the inquiry

115
00:11:10,052 --> 00:11:25,701
as an actual intention, you'd be surprised that in those receptive moments insights arise naturally, because although we make a distinction between awareness and this intuitive intelligence, they're two sides of the same coin.

116
00:11:26,181 --> 00:11:29,967
One is passive, receiving, and one is active in insight.

117
00:11:31,011 --> 00:11:44,346
So it's the same, you know, when something goes wrong, I don't know, you can't find something or something goes wrong with your car or something, you open the bonnet, see, first you look.

118
00:11:44,917 --> 00:11:46,799
Look, that's the receiving.

119
00:11:47,441 --> 00:11:49,303
And then you see, the engine's gone.

120
00:11:50,645 --> 00:11:59,318
It's like there's always that listening and then understanding, hearing and then listening, understanding.

121
00:11:59,339 --> 00:12:03,684
So there's always this sort of flick from the passive to the active.

122
00:12:05,419 --> 00:12:13,034
So after lunch, if you want to take a walk around the paddock or whatever, then just practice that.

123
00:12:13,134 --> 00:12:20,490
You can practice walking up and down in meditation, but with the attitude of just relaxing into the present moment, wide awake.

124
00:12:22,815 --> 00:12:25,419
And then, by all means, feel free to take a rest.
